es to efforts to increase the number of women scientists and yet progress in attracting more women to science has stalled the 2009 national academies report gender differences at critical transitions stresses that research must explore gender differences in the obligations outside of professional responsibilities in order to understand women's career choices and outcomes more fully if universities offered a benefit to pay someone else to do that work scientists would have more time to spend on the jobs they re trained for on april 7th the clayman institute hosted a panel discussion on this innovative proposal titled housework matters donate make a donation social links facebook twitter youtube scribd contact serra house 589 capistrano way stanford ca 94305 8640 map 650 723 1994 gender email stanford edu
